TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Bond Scheduling Problem of the Multi-Subsidiary Holding Company
AU  - Baker, Kenneth R.
AU  - Vander Weide, James H.
Y1  - 1982/07/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.28.7.738
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.28.7.738
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 738
EP  - 748
VL  - 28
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper presents a decision-theoretic model of the bond scheduling problem faced by a multi-subsidiary holding company such as AT&T or GTE. The objective is to minimize the total cost of bond flotations across all subsidiaries, where total cost is the sum of the yield paid to investors, the flotation expense associated with the preparation of each issue and the opportunity expense to each subsidiary of not meeting its request at the desired time. Our model suggests that the timing of bond issues is primarily a problem in trading off the diseconomies of issuing many bonds in one month with the penalty costs of delay. An efficient dynamic programming algorithm for solving the problem is also presented along with an example.
AB  - This paper presents a decision-theoretic model of the bond scheduling problem faced by a multi-subsidiary holding company such as AT&T or GTE. The objective is to minimize the total cost of bond flotations across all subsidiaries, where total cost is the sum of the yield paid to investors, the flotation expense associated with the preparation of each issue and the opportunity expense to each subsidiary of not meeting its request at the desired time. Our model suggests that the timing of bond issues is primarily a problem in trading off the diseconomies of issuing many bonds in one month with the penalty costs of delay. An efficient dynamic programming algorithm for solving the problem is also presented along with an example.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.28.7.738
